docs.abstract: As more suburbanites move downtown, developers are seeking new land for housing and offices, creating opportunities for owners of empty parking lots.
docs.snippet: As more suburbanites move downtown, developers are seeking new land for housing and offices, creating opportunities for owners of empty parking lots.
docs.lead_paragraph: As the lure of urban living pulls more residents from the suburbs, developers are scooping up prime real estate in downtowns across the United States. Soaring property values have created opportunities for owners of an overlooked, underdeveloped asset: the surface parking lot.

headline.main: Parking Lots, Once Asphalt Wasteland, Become Golden Opportunities
headline.print_headline: Prime Urban Lots (Parking Included, of Course)

headline.main: Turkey Questions Pilots About Carlos Ghosn’s Escape From Japan

docs.abstract: Walmart has taken stands on several controversial issues, but the retailer has been careful to alienate as few customers as possible while doing so.
docs.snippet: Walmart has taken stands on several controversial issues, but the retailer has been careful to alienate as few customers as possible while doing so.
docs.lead_paragraph: Walmart is getting out of the vaping business, but still sells cigarettes. It is working to reduce plastic packaging for the products on its shelves, but continues to use plastic grocery bags in its checkout lines. After a gunman killed 22 people at a Walmart in El Paso this summer, the retailer said it would no longer offer certain types of ammunition, but stopped short of barring customers from carrying their guns into stores.

headline.main: Walmart’s Strategy When Wading Into Culture Wars: Offend Few
headline.print_headline: Treading A Fine Line Amid Wars Over Culture

docs.lead_paragraph: In the 10 months since Richard Plepler stepped down as HBO’s chief executive, the final season of “Game of Thrones” came and went, CBS and Viacom merged, and Disney and Apple rolled out new streaming services.

headline.main: Apple Deal Returns Former HBO Boss Richard Plepler to Spotlight
headline.print_headline: After HBO, A Fresh Start With Apple

docs.abstract: In Campbellsville, Ky., the tech giant’s influences abound. The profits, not so much.
docs.snippet: In Campbellsville, Ky., the tech giant’s influences abound. The profits, not so much.
docs.lead_paragraph: CAMPBELLSVILLE, Ky. — In the late 1990s, the town of Campbellsville in central Kentucky suffered a powerful jolt when its Fruit of the Loom textile plant closed. Thousands of jobs making underwear went to Central America, taking the community’s pride with them.

headline.main: Prime Anchor: An Amazon Warehouse Town Dreams of a Better Life
headline.print_headline: Town Feels Tech Giant’s Influence, but Tastes Little of Its Profits

docs.abstract: The lawsuit claims the company targeted minority women and children despite being aware of the risk of asbestos in talc.
docs.snippet: The lawsuit claims the company targeted minority women and children despite being aware of the risk of asbestos in talc.
docs.lead_paragraph: The accusations in a new lawsuit against Johnson & Johnson sound familiar: The consumer goods giant knew for decades that its baby powder and other talc-based products were contaminated with carcinogenic asbestos, but continued to market the items.

headline.main: Johnson & Johnson Sued Over Baby Powder by New Mexico
